<!-- What is map() ?
In simple terms, the map function calls a function once for each element in an array. Basically, it iterates over each element or item in an array and creates a new array based on what is returned by the function.

What is it used for?
It is commonly used when you want to take an array, make some changes on the items or apply a function on it, and get a new array.

The Basic syntax is Using Arrow Funtion:
map((element, index, array) => {
   //return something
})

ex:

const array = [3,1,15,1,5,3,23]
//map the array
array.map((el) =>{
    console.log(el)
})

ex:
const users = [
  { firstName: "john", lastName: "doe" },
  { firstName: "Daniel", lastName: "steve" },
  { firstName: "mike", lastName: "hoff" },
];
//map the array and display only first names
users.map((el) => {
  console.log(el.firstName);
});

ex:
const materials = ['Hydrogen', 'Helium', 'Lithium', 'Beryllium'];
const data = materials.map((material) => material.length);
console.log(data);

React Ex:

export default function SkillSet() {
    const skillset = ['Java', 'Spring Boot', 'Microservice', 'MySQL', 'MongoDB'];
    return (
        <>
            {skillset.map((item, index) => (
                <span key={index}>
                    <span className="badge badge-pill bg-info me-2">{item}</span>
                </span>
            ))}
        </>
    )
}


Using Traditional Function :
ex: 
const numbers = [65, 44, 12, 4];
const newArr = numbers.map(myFunction)

function myFunction(num) {
  return num * 10;
}

In React :

import React from 'react';

export default function App() {
 const applicants = [ {
    name: 'Joe', work: 'freelance-developer',
    blogs: '54', websites: '32',
    hackathons: '6', location: 'morocco', id: '0',
  },
  {
    name: 'janet', work: 'fullstack-developer', 
    blogs: '34', websites: '12', 
    hackathons: '8', location: 'Mozambique', id: '1',
  },

 ];
  return (
    <>
    {
      applicants.map(function(applicant) 
      {
            return 
            (
            <div key={applicant.id}>
                <p>Applicant Name: {applicant.name}</p>
                <p>Applicant location: {applicant.location}</p>
                <p>Hackathons participated: {applicant.hackathons}</p>
            </div>
            )
      })
    }
    </>
  );
};




 -->
